        args='{"prompt": "In {{spacex_s1}}, retrieve the definitions or descriptions of \\"Launch Services\\" revenue and \\"Launch & Development\\" revenue categories. Also retrieve any discussion of how internal Starlink launches are treated in the revenue figures versus external customer launches. Look for any disclosure about pricing per launch, contract values per mission, or revenue recognition methodology for launch services."}',
        parsed_args={
            'prompt': 'In {{spacex_s1}}, retrieve the definitions or descriptions of "Launch Services" revenue and "Launch & Development" revenue categories. Also retrieve any discussion of how internal Starlink launches are treated in the revenue figures versus external customer launches. Look for any disclosure about pricing per launch, contract values per mission, or revenue recognition methodology for launch services.'
        }
    ),
    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided excerpts, here is a summary of the requested information regarding the Space segment\'s revenue categories, the treatment of internal launches, and revenue recognition methodology.\n\n### **1. Definitions of Revenue Categories**\n\n**Launch Services:**\n*   **Description:** Revenue derived from the deployment of customer payloads to their intended orbits for both commercial and government customers using Falcon 9 and Falcon Heavy.\n*   **Contract Duration:** Fixed-price contracts ranging from **one to five years**.\n*   **Revenue Recognition:** Recognized at a **point in time**, upon the launch or deployment of the customer’s payload.\n\n**Launch & Development:**\n*   **Description:** Revenue derived from the development of spacecraft and the provision of launch and mission services for government agency space programs using Falcon 9, Falcon Heavy, Starship, and Dragon.\n*   **Contract Duration:** Fixed-price contracts that can range from **one to fourteen years**.\n*   **Revenue Recognition:** Recognized **over time** as performance creates an asset with no alternative use and an enforceable right to payment exists.\n\n### **2. Treatment of Internal (Starlink) Launches vs. External Customer Launches**\n\n*   **Internal Launches (Starlink):** Launches dedicated to deploying the company\'s own Starlink satellites are **not included in Space segment revenue**. The associated launch costs are **capitalized** as part of "satellites in Property, plant, and equipment, net" within the Connectivity segment and depreciated over time.\n*   **External Customer Launches:** Only launches where an external customer\'s payload is the primary mission are recognized as revenue in the Space segment. A launch is designated as a "customer launch" if an external customer payload constitutes the primary payload and the mission parameters are designed around that payload\'s requirements.\n*   **Capacity Allocation:** The company allocates a significant amount of launch capacity to its internal Connectivity segment (for Starlink) and expects to allocate a significant amount to its AI segment in the future. As a result, **Space segment revenue only reflects external customer launches and activities**.\n\n### **3. Revenue Recognition Methodology**\n\nThe company recognizes revenue as control transfers to the customer, using two primary methods:\n\n*   **Point-in-Time Recognition (Primarily for Launch Services):** Revenue and related costs are deferred and recognized only upon the launch or deployment of the customer’s spacecraft to its intended orbit. This is due to the interchangeability of flight hardware and minimal unique engineering costs.\n*   **Over-Time Recognition (For Launch & Development and some Connectivity contracts):** Used when performance creates an asset with no alternative use and the company has an enforceable right to payment. Progress is measured using the **cost-to-cost input method**, where revenue is recognized based on costs incurred to date relative to total estimated costs at completion. Significant judgment is required to estimate total contract costs.\n\n### **4. Pricing and Contract Values**\n\nThe provided excerpts do not disclose specific **pricing per launch** or **exact contract values per mission**. The financial discussion focuses on revenue trends at the segment level (e.g., Launch Services revenue decreased by $236 million quarter-over-quarter due to fewer customer launches) and the mix between the two revenue types (e.g., Launch Services made up 53.3% of Space revenue in Q1 2026 vs. 46.7% for Launch & Development).\n\n**Key Financial Trend:** The company expects Space revenue growth to be slower than total company growth as internal launches absorb most new capacity. It also anticipates **Launch & Development** will represent a larger portion of Space revenue in the future due to long-term government contracts.',
