2026-06-10 16:41:07,575 DEBUG Tool call: submit_final_result({'final_result': '\n## Implied Revenue-Per-Launch Comparison: SpaceX vs. Rocket Lab\n\n---\n\n### 1. Data Extracted from Filings\n\n**SpaceX S-1 (filed May 20, 2026) — FY2025 figures:**\n- Launch Services revenue: **$2,576 million**\n- Launch & Development revenue: $1,510 million\n- Total Space segment revenue: $4,086 million\n- Total Falcon launches: 165\n- External customer launches: **43**\n- Internal (Starlink) launches: 122\n- Flight-proven booster launches: 157 of 165 (**95.2% reuse rate**)\n\n**Rocket Lab 10-K (filed February 26, 2026) — FY2025 figures:**\n- Launch Services segment revenue: **$199.0 million**\n- Electron launches: **21**\n\n---\n\n### 2. Implied Revenue-Per-Launch Proxy Construction\n\n**SpaceX** — The S-1 confirms that internal Starlink launches do **not** generate Space segment revenue; associated costs are capitalized as satellite PP&E within the Connectivity segment. Therefore, Launch Services revenue ($2,576M) maps exclusively to the 43 external customer launches:\n\n| Metric | FY2023 | FY2024 | FY2025 |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Launch Services Revenue ($M) | $1,964 | $2,584 | $2,576 |\n| Customer Launches | 33 | 45 | 43 |\n| **Implied Rev/Customer Launch ($M)** | **$59.52** | **$57.42** | **$59.91** |\n\n**Rocket Lab** — Launch Services revenue maps directly and entirely to Electron launch count:\n\n| Metric | FY2023 | FY2024 | FY2025 |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Launch Services Revenue ($M) | $71.9 | $125.4 | $199.0 |\n| Electron Launches | 10 | 16 | 21 |\n| **Implied Rev/Launch ($M)** | **$7.19** | **$7.84** | **$9.48** |\n\n---\n\n### 3. Directional Comparison\n\n| Metric | FY2023 | FY2024 | FY2025 |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| SpaceX implied rev/launch | $59.52M | $57.42M | $59.91M |\n| Rocket Lab implied rev/launch | $7.19M | $7.84M | $9.48M |\n| **SpaceX / Rocket Lab ratio** | **8.3x** | **7.3x** | **6.3x** |\n\nSpaceX\'s implied per-launch revenue is approximately **6.3x** Rocket Lab\'s as of FY2025, a ratio that has been narrowing (from 8.3x in FY2023) as Rocket Lab\'s Electron pricing trends upward and its launch cadence scales.\n\nSpaceX\'s per-launch figure is remarkably stable at ~$57–60M across all three years, consistent with the widely reported Falcon 9 commercial list price.\n\n---\n\n### 4. What the Comparison Reveals About Vertical Integration and Reusability\n\n**Reusability does not compress per-launch revenue — it compresses per-launch cost.** SpaceX achieved a 95.2% flight-proven booster reuse rate in FY2025 (157 of 165 Falcon launches), yet its implied revenue per customer launch held steady at ~$60M. This indicates that the cost savings from reusability flow almost entirely to **margin expansion**, not to customer price reductions. SpaceX maintains pricing power because no competitor matches Falcon 9\'s payload capacity (~22,800 kg to LEO), reliability record, and schedule cadence.\n\n**Vertical integration amplifies this margin effect.** SpaceX manufactures its own engines (Merlin/Raptor), structures, avionics, and software in-house. This eliminates supplier markup and allows iterative cost reduction on reused hardware. The combination of vertical integration and high-frequency reuse means SpaceX\'s cost per launch is likely a fraction of its $60M revenue — a margin structure unavailable to Rocket Lab, whose expendable Electron vehicles require new hardware for every mission.\n\n**Rocket Lab\'s lower per-launch revenue reflects a fundamentally different vehicle class.** Electron delivers ~300 kg to LEO (vs. Falcon 9\'s ~22,800 kg), targeting the small-satellite niche at ~$7–10M per mission. The revenue-per-kg-to-LEO comparison is more informative:\n- SpaceX: ~$59.91M / ~22,800 kg ≈ **$2,628/kg** (Falcon 9 to LEO)\n- Rocket Lab: ~$9.48M / ~300 kg ≈ **$31,587/kg** (Electron to LEO)\n\nSpaceX\'s ~12x lower cost per kilogram of payload reflects the economies of scale unlocked by vehicle size, reusability, and launch cadence.\n\n**The narrowing ratio (8.3x → 6.3x) suggests Rocket Lab is gaining pricing power** as its manifest grows, reliability is proven, and small-launch alternatives contract. But the structural gap will persist until Rocket Lab\'s reusable Neutron vehicle (targeting ~13,000 kg to LEO) enters service.\n\n---\n\n### 5. The Critical Missing Disclosure: Present for Rocket Lab, Absent for SpaceX\n\nThe comparison is **approximate, not precise**, because the SpaceX S-1 lacks a disclosure that Rocket Lab\'s 10-K provides implicitly:\n\n> **A direct, explicit mapping of per-launch revenue to individual vehicle/mission type — i.e., an average revenue per launch figure, or a breakout of Launch Services revenue by vehicle (Falcon 9 vs. Falcon Heavy) and by customer type (commercial vs. government).**\n\nSpecifically:\n\n1. **Rocket Lab\'s Launch Services segment is a single-product business.** Electron is the only launch vehicle in service. Launch Services revenue and Electron launch count are reported as directly corresponding KPIs, making the per-launch calculation unambiguous: $199.0M ÷ 21 = $9.48M.\n\n2. **SpaceX\'s Launch Services revenue is a blended figure across multiple vehicle configurations and customer types.** The 43 customer launches in FY2025 include:\n   - Falcon 9 and Falcon Heavy missions at materially different price points\n   - Commercial and government (NASA, DoD) missions with different contract structures\n   - Missions to different orbits (LEO, GTO, GEO, cislunar) with different complexity and pricing\n\n   The S-1 does **not** disclose:\n   - How many of the 43 customer launches were Falcon Heavy vs. Falcon 9\n   - Average revenue per mission by vehicle type or customer type\n   - A weighted-average selling price per launch\n\nWithout this disaggregation, the $59.91M figure is a **blended proxy** that could mask significant pricing variation — a Falcon Heavy mission may command $90–150M while a rideshare or government bulk-purchase Falcon 9 mission may be significantly lower than $60M.\n\n**The specific disclosure required for precision:** An "average revenue per launch" KPI or a disaggregation table breaking Launch Services revenue into Falcon 9 commercial, Falcon 9 government, and Falcon Heavy subcategories with associated launch counts — analogous to how Rocket Lab\'s single-product structure naturally produces this mapping.\n\n---\n\n### Sources\n\n| Source | URL |\n|---|---|\n| SpaceX S-1 (filed May 20, 2026) | https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm |\n| Rocket Lab 10-K (FY2025, filed Feb 26, 2026) | https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1819994/000181999426000013/rklb-20251231.htm |\n'})
